I would, and I did! Sorry, folks, but for me, whenever I listen to a
selection
of Goldsmith's post-1990 output, a feeling of depressing same-ness
settles over me. The same orchestrations. The same rhythms. The same
approach to scoring action, suspense, tender moments. The same brass
writing. The same figures in the strings. The wonderful sense of
freshness,
of experimentation, that so often marked his earlier (and greatest)
scores
is almost entirely gone. I am almost always disappointed by what I
hear
in his later work, and I am almost always thrilled deeply by what I
hear in
what had gone before.

I own a lot of these scores, and I've listened to each and every one
of them
multiple times in various attempts to find whatever it is in them that
I'm
missing, and almost without exception, I find that it all sounds
almost
entirely the same, with only the melodies to make the difference (or a
few
ethnic percussion instruments thrown in). Now, that's not to say that
I
detest all that music, since I do think there are some keepers there
(Timeline,
Star Trek First Contact, Powder, LA Confidential), but even those
don't even
begin to approach in quality scores like Planet of the Apes,
Chinatown,
the Omen trilogy, Patton, Tora!Tora!Tora!, or the towering Legend.
